  "prompt": "Is money laundering a contravention of legal standards?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a **contravention (violation) of legal standards** in virtually every jurisdiction around the world.\n\nHere's why:\n\n*   **It's a Criminal Offense:** Money laundering is a specifically defined criminal offense under national and international laws. These laws prohibit the process of concealing the origins of illegally obtained money, making it appear legitimate.\n*   **Violation of Financial Regulations:** Money laundering involves violating regulations related to financial transparency, reporting requirements, and anti-money laundering (AML) compliance that financial institutions must adhere to.\n*   **International Agreements and Treaties:** Numerous international agreements and treaties, such as those established by the Financial Action Task Force (FATF), obligate signatory nations to criminalize money laundering and implement measures to combat it. This makes it a violation of international legal standards as well.\n\nIn short, the entire purpose of money laundering is to circumvent legal standards designed to prevent and punish illegal activities.\n\n**Consequences of Money Laundering:**\n\n*   Criminal prosecution\n*   Imprisonment\n*   Fines\n*   Asset forfeiture\n*   Damage to reputation\n\nTherefore, money laundering is undoubtedly a serious breach of legal standards.\n",
